---
source: crates/splitter-cli/tests/help_snapshots.rs
expression: output
---
Start the Splitter background daemon. The daemon binds a TCP
signaling server, registers an mDNS service record (_splitter._tcp.local.),
starts a device hot-plug watcher, and optionally enables a Prometheus metrics endpoint.

After startup it prints the machine-readable banner:
READY port=<N>
where <N> is the actual TCP port. Supervisor scripts must wait for this line before
issuing REPL commands via stdin.

On first launch a UUID identity is written to the platform config directory:
macOS   — ~/Library/Application Support/Splitter/<identity>/
Linux   — ~/.config/Splitter/<identity>/
Windows — %APPDATA%\Splitter\<identity>\

REPL quick reference (run `splitter-cli --help` for the full list):
peers                     list mDNS-discovered peers
connect <name|id>         open a TCP signaling link to a peer
accept <n>                trust a pending HELLO from peer at index <n>
open <name|id>            open a Session with a connected peer
sessions                  list active sessions and streams
stream open --from in:0 --to <peer>:out:0 --session <UUID>
stream stats              live per-stream statistics table
quit                      graceful shutdown

Examples:
splitter-cli daemon
splitter-cli daemon --signaling-port 5100 --peer-name "Studio Mac"
splitter-cli daemon --identity-dir ~/.splitter/alice

Usage: splitter-cli daemon [OPTIONS]

Options:
      --signaling-port <SIGNALING_PORT>
          [default: 7000]

      --peer-name <PEER_NAME>
          

      --identity-dir <IDENTITY_DIR>
          

  -h, --help
          Print help (see a summary with '-h')
